To create an LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor with Arduino, you will need to follow several steps.

First, you need to install the LiquidCrystal\_I2C library in the Arduino IDE. You can find this library by going to Tools > Manage Libraries, searching for "LiquidCrystal I2C," and installing the library by Frank de Brabander [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].

Next, you need to connect the temperature sensor and potentiometer to the Arduino board. For the temperature sensor, you can use the LM35 temperature sensor, which is powered by the Arduino board via VCC and GND pins. The analog output pin of the LM35 temperature sensor should be connected to the analog input pin A0 of Arduino [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

For the potentiometer, you can use a 10 K Ohm potentiometer, where the second pin is connected to pin 3 of the LCD, and the first pin of the potentiometer is connected to +VCC. The third pin of the potentiometer is connected to the contrast pin of the LCD [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

Once you have connected the temperature sensor and potentiometer to the Arduino board, you can write the code to display the temperature on the LCD. You can find a detailed instruction, code, wiring diagram, video tutorial, and line-by-line code explanation on how to use Arduino to read temperature from DS18B20 sensor and display temperature on LCD on ArduinoGetStarted [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)

A product designer is responsible for creating new products or improving existing ones. The process typically involves the following steps:

1. Research and Analysis: The designer conducts market research to understand the needs and preferences of the target audience. They also analyze the competition and identify any gaps in the market.
2. Concept Development: Based on the research, the designer develops several concepts for the new product. They sketch or create digital renderings of the concepts to visualize the product.
3. Prototyping: The designer creates a prototype of the most promising concept. This can be a physical model or a digital simulation. The prototype is used to test the product's functionality, usability, and aesthetics.
4. Testing and Evaluation: The prototype is tested with users to gather feedback. The designer evaluates the feedback and makes any necessary adjustments to the design.
5. Production: Once the design is finalized, the designer works with manufacturers to produce the product. They may also be involved in the marketing and sales of the product.
6. Iteration: The designer continues to iterate on the design based on user feedback and market trends. They may also work on new versions of the product to keep it fresh and relevant.

Throughout the process, the product designer must consider factors such as cost, materials, manufacturing processes, and sustainability. They must also ensure that the product meets safety and regulatory requirements.
